Regular Languages

  • A language is called a regular language if some finite automaton recognizes it
    • It is only regular iff some NFA recognizes it

Finite Automaton

  • Good for models with limited amount of memory
  • Example of a finite automaton diagram:
  • This is called a state diagram
    • It has three states, \(q_1, q_2, q_3\).
    • \(q_1\) is the starting state
    • \(q_2\) is the accept state, hence the double circle around it
    • The arrows are called transitions
  • Autamota create an output that is either accept or reject
    • The output is accept if the string ends in the accept state
      • We say that the string is accepted
  • The above state diagram reads in the following way on input string \(1101\):
  • Formal definition:
  • The formal definition of the above state diagram is as follows:
  • Say that \(A\) is a set of all of the strings that is accepted by the finite automaton (or machine) \(M\).
    • It is said that \(A\) is the language of the machine in this case and is written as \(L(M) = A\).
    • This is verbalized as \(M\) recognizes \(A\) or \(M\) accepts \(A\).
  • A machine can accept many strings but will always recognize only one language
    • A machine that accepts no strings still accepts a language, the empty language, \(\varnothing\)
  • In the above example, the language would be:
    \(A = \left\{w | w ~\text{contains at least one 1 and an even number of 0s follow the last 1}\right\}\)

Designing a Finite Automaton

  • The goal is to design a machine that will recognize the language \(L = \left\{w | w ~\text{contains an odd number of ones}\right\}~\) in the alphabet \(\Sigma = \left\{0, 1\right\}\)
  • All you need to remember is whether the number of ones seen sof ar is even or odd
    • If you read a \(1\), flip states. If you read a \(0\), stay in the same state
  • Two states needed:
  • Assign transitions by seeing how to go from one possibility to another based on reading a symbol
    • i.e. if you’re in \(q_{even}\) and you read a \(1\), go to \(q_{odd}\) and vice versa
    • if you’re in either state and you read a \(0\), stay there
  • Determine which will be your starting and accepting states.
    • You want to have an odd number of ones so the accept state should be \(q_{odd}\)
    • The starting state should be \(q_{even}\) because having no ones would be an even number of them.

Regular Operators

  • Like a tool for regular languages, regular operators are operations specifically designed for manipulating regular languages
  • Regular languages are defined as follows:
    • Let \(A\) and \(B\) be languages. We define regular operations union, concatenation, and star as:
      • Union: \(A \cup B = \left\{x | x \in A ~\text{or}~ x \in B\right\}\)
      • Concatenation: \(A\circ B = \left\{xy | x \in A ~\text{and}~ y \in B\right\}\)
      • Star: \(A^* = \left\{x_1x_2...x_k | k \geq 0 ~\text{and each}~ x_i \in A\right\}\)
  • Union takes all of the strings in both \(A\) and \(B\) and lumps them together into one language
  • Concatenation attaches a string from \(A\) onto the front of a string from \(B\) in all possible ways to get the strings in the new language
  • Star is a unary operation that attaches any number of strings in \(A\) together to get a string in a new language. It includes \(0\) as a possibility and the empty string \(\lambda\) is always a member of the language
  • An example of how these operators work is as follows:

Closure Under Regular Operators

  • Union: The class of regular languages is closed under the union operation. In other words, if \(A_1\) and \(A_2\) are regular languages, then so is \(A_1 \cup A_2\)
    • Proof: Let \(M_1\) recognize \(A_1\) where \(M_1 = \left(Q_1, \Sigma, \delta_1, q_1, F_1\right)\) and \(M_2\) recognize \(A_2\) where \(M_2 = \left(Q_2, \Sigma, \delta_2, q_2, F_2\right)\)
      • Construct \(M\) to recognize \(A_1 \cup A_2\) where \(M = \left(Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_o, F\right)\)
        • \(Q = \left\{(r_1, r_2) | r_1 \in Q_1 ~\text{and}~ r_2 \in Q_2\right\}\)
          This is the cartesian product of sets \(Q_1\) and \(Q_2\), written as \(Q_1 \times Q_2\). It is the set of all pairs of states, the first from \(Q_1\) and the second from \(Q_2\).
        • \(\Sigma\), the alphabet, is the same as in \(M_1\) and \(M_2\). In this theorem (and in all subsequent similar theorems) we assume for simplicity that both \(M_1\) and \(M_2\) have the same input alphabet \(\Sigma\). The theorem remains true if they have different alphabets, you would just have to modify the proff to let \(\Sigma = \Sigma_1 \cup \Sigma_2\)
        • \(\delta\), the transition function, is defined as follows:
          For each \((r_1, r_2) \in Q\) and each \(a \in \Sigma\), let
          \(\delta((r_1, r_2), a) = \left(\delta_1(r_1, a), \delta_2(r_2, a)\right)\)
          Hence \(\delta\) gets a state of \(M\) (which is actually a pair of states from \(M_1\) and \(M_2\)), together with an input symbol, and returns \(M's\) next state.
        • \(q_o\) is the pair \((q_1, q_2)\)
        • \(F\) is the set of paris in which either member is an accept state of \(M_1\) or \(M_2\). We can write it as
          \(F = \left\{(r_1, r_2) | r_1 \in F ~\text{or}~ r_2 \in F_2\right\}\)
          This expression is the same as \(F = (F_1 \times Q_2) \cup (Q_1 \times F_2)\)
    • This is the entire construction for the machine \(M\) that recognizes \(A_1 \cup A_2\)
  • Concatenation: The class of regular languages is closed under the concatenation operation. In other words, if \(A_1\) and \(A_2\) are regular languages then so is \(A_1 \circ A_2\).
    • This is similar to the proof above. However, instead of constructing a machine that will accept if either \(M_1\) or \(M_2\) accept, it must accept if the input can be broken into two pieces, one of which will be accepted by \(M_1\) and the other which will be accepted by \(M_2\). The issue arises with not knowing where to break the input; we need nondeterminism to solve this (jump to NFAs).

DFAs

  • DFA stands for deterministic finite automaton
  • Has exactly one exiting transition arrow for each symbol in the alphabet and does not allow for \(\lambda\) transitions
  • The transition function takes a state and an input symbol and produces the next state

NFAs

  • NFA stands for nondeterministic finite automaton
  • In a nondeterministic machine, several choices may exist for the next state at any point
  • Compared to the automaton shown above, NFAs have additional features such as \(\lambda\) transitions and the allowance of not having an arrow for each symbol in the alphabet
  • When there is an input that has multiple ways to proceed, the machine starts running all choices in parallel; each copy of the machine takes a different way to proceed
    • The splitting continues if the copy comes across another need to split
    • The copies of the machine die if there are no more options for it to proceed
    • If any of the copies accept, the entire NFA accepts
  • You can see the difference between NFAs and DFAs in a tree structure
  • The example NFA above would have a tree that looks like the following for an input string 010110
  • After analyzing the NFA, it can be seen taht it will accept all strings that contain either \(101\) or \(11\) as a substring. That is:
    \(L = \left\{w | 101 \in w ~\text{or}~ 11 \in w\right\}\)
  • It should be noted that every NFA can be converted into an equivalent DFA
    • Sometimes constructing an NFA is easier than constructing a DFA
    • For example, below is the DFA equivalent of the NFA example from above
  • Formal Definition
    • Different from a DFA in the fact that the transition function takes a state and an input symbol or the empty string and produces the set of possible next states
    • An NFA is a 5-tuple \((Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_o, F)\) where:
      • \(Q\) is a finite set of states
      • \(\Sigma\) is a finite alphabet
      • \(\delta: Q \times \Sigma_{\lambda} \to P(Q)\) is the transition function
      • \(q_o \in Q\) is the start state
      • \(F \subset Q\) is the set of accept states
    • Below is the formal definition of the above NFA example

    • The states will be \(P(\Sigma)\)
    • In this example, \(\Sigma = \{1, 2, 3\}\) so the DFA will have states \(\{\varnothing, \{1\}, \{2\}, \{3\}, \{1, 2\}, \{1, 3\}, \{2, 3\}, \{1, 2, 3\}\}\)
  • You need to determine the start and accept states of the DFA \(D\).
    • The starting state(s) will be those that are reachable from 1 by traveling along \(\lambda\) arrows, plus 1 itself.
      • A \(\lambda\) arrow goes from state 1 to state 3, so the starting state for \(D\) will be state \(\left\{1, 3\right\}\) (which is shown below)

  • You can remove the unnecessary states
    • Unnecessary states are those that do not have an arrow going into them

Closure Under the Regular Operations

  • Union: The class of regular languages is closed under the union operation
    • Proof: Let \(N_1 = (Q_1, \Sigma, \delta_1, q_1, F_1)\) recognize \(A_1\) and \(N_2 = (Q_2, \Sigma, \delta_2, q_2, F_2)\) recognize \(A_2\)

      • The state \(q_o\) is the start state of \(N\)
      • The set of accept states \(F = F_1 \cup F_2\)
        The accept states of \(N\) are all the accept states of \(N_1\) and \(N_2\). That way, \(N\) accepts if either \(N_1\) accepts or \(N_2\) accepts

      Construct \(N = (Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_1, F_2)\) to recognize \(A_1 \circ A_2\)
      • \(Q = Q_1 \cup A_2\)
        The states of \(N\) are all the states of \(N_1\) and \(N_2\)
      • The state \(q_1\) is the sae as the start state of \(N_1\)
      • The accept states \(F_2\) are the same as the accept states of \(N_2\)

      Construct \(N = (Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_o, F)\) recognize \(A_1^*\)

        The states of \(N\) are the states of \(N_1\) plus a new start state
      • The state \(q_o\) is the new start state
      • \(F = \{q_o\} \cup F_1\)
        the accept states are the old accept states plus the new start state

Regular Expressions

  • A regular expression is the use of regular operations to build up expressions describing languages
    • An example is \((0 \cup 1)0^*\)
  • Arithmetic expressions such as \((5 + 3) \times 4\) result in a numeric value, \(32\) for this specific example. Regular expressions have a similar result; their value is a language
    • You get the language by dissolving the regular expression into parts
  • From the above example:
    • \(0\) and \(1\) are shorthand for \(\{0\} ~\text{and}~ \{1\}\), respectively. This means that \((0 \cup 1)\) translates to \((\{0\} \cup \{1\})\) which is part of the language \(\{0, 1\}\)
    • The part \(0^*\) is shorthand for \(\{0^*\}\) which means that its value is the language of all strings containing any number of \(0s\)
    • Lastly, similar to the \(\times\) expression in arithmetic expressions, the \(\circ\) operation is often implied in regular expressions. It is assumed that \((0 \cup 1)0^*\) translates to \((0 \cup 1) \circ 0^*\)
      • The concatenation, as discussed previously, attaches the strings to obtain an entire expression
  • Formal Definition:
    • Say that \(R\) is a regular expression if \(R\) is:
      • \(a\) for some \(a \in \Sigma\)
      • \(\lambda\)
      • \(\varnothing\)
      • \((R_1 \cup R_2)\) where \(R_1\) and \(R_2\) are regular expressions
      • \((R_1 \circ R_2)\) where \(R_1\) and \(R_2\) are regular expressions
      • \((R_1^*)\) where \(R_1\) is a regular expression
  • Order of Operations for Regular Expressions
    • Parenthesis may be omitted in an expression. The order of operations is:
      • Star
      • Concatenation
      • Union
  • \(R^+\) is shorthand for \(RR^*\)
    • In other words, where \(R*\) contains all of the strings containing any number of concatenations of \(R\) including \(0\), \(R^+\) must contain at least one or more concatenations of \(R\)
  • Concatenating any set to \(\varnothing\) yields \(\varnothing\)

Equivalence with Finite Automata

  • A language is regular iff some regular expression describes it
    • This will be broken into two steps due to the iff, first we will look at:
      If a language is described by a regular expression, then it is regular
    • Proof: Convert \(R\) into an NFA \(N\). Consider the six cases in the formal definition of regular expressions
    • \(R = a\) for some \(a \in \Sigma\). Then \(L(R) = \{a\}\), and the following NFA recognizes \(L(R)\)
    • \(R = \lambda\). Then \(L(R) = \{\lambda\}\) and the following NFA recognizes \(L(R)\)
    • \(R = \varnothing\). Then \(L(R) = \varnothing\) and the following NFA recognizes \(L(R)\)
    • \(R = R_1 \cup R_2\)
    • \(R = R_1 \circ R_2\)
    • \(R = R_1^*\)
      • For these last three cases, we use the constructions given in the proofs of regular languages being closed under regular operations. In other words, we create the NFA for \(R\) from the NFAs for \(R_1\) and \(R_2\) and the appropriate closure construction. An example is shown at the end of the section
  • If a language is regular, then it is described by a regular expression
    • This proof requires knowledge about GNFAs which are discussed in the section below
    • Proof: Let \(M\) be the \(DFA\) for language \(A\)
      • Convert \(M\) to a GNFA \(G\) by adding a new start and new accept state and add transitional arrows as necessary
      • The conversion uses recursion unless there are only two states
        • CONVERT(G)
          • Let \(k\) be the number of states in \(G\)
          • If \(k = 2, G\) must consist of a start state and accept state with a single arrow between them labeled with a regular expression \(R\), return \(R\)
          • If \(k > 2\), select any state \(q_{rip} \in Q\) that is not the starting or accepting state
            • Let \(G'\) be the new GNFA with \(q_{rip} \notin Q\), compute CONVERT(G') and return its value
    • Next it needs to be proven that CONVERT(G) returns the correct value. This is done with induction
      • Base Case: Prove that CONVERT(G) is equivalent to \(G\) for \(k = 2\)
        • If \(G\) only has 2 states, it can only have a single arrow that goes from the start state to the accept state
        • The regular expression label on this arrow describes all of the strings accepted by \(G\), therefore the claim is true for \(k = 2\)
      • Induction Step: Assume that the claim is true for \(k - 1\) states and use the assumption to prove that it is true for \(k\) states
      • First show that \(G\) and \(G'\) recognize the same language
        • If \(G\) accepts some input \(w\), we know that \(G\) enters a sequence of states
          \(q_{start}, q_1, q_2, ..., q_{accept}\)
        • If none of the states are the removed state \(q_{rip}\), then we know that \(G'\) also accepts \(w\) because each of the new regular expressions used as labels in \(G'\) come from the union of old regular expressions
        • If \(q_{rip}\) does appear, removing each run of consecutive \(q_{rip}\) states is accepted by \(G'\). The other states, \(q_i\) and \(q_j\), are then labeled with the regular expression that describes the collection of strings both between the two states directly and the routes taken via \(q_{rip}\) on \(G\), so therefore \(G'\) accepts as well.
        • Take the reverse: suppose \(G'\) accepts an input string \(w\). Each arrow between states in \(G'\) describes the collection of strings it takes to go between those states either directly or indirectly in \(G\), who also accepts \(w\). Therefore \(G\) and \(G'\) are equivalent.
  • Example: Convert \((ab \cup a)^*\) to an NFA

GNFAs

  • GNFA stands for generalized nondeterministic finite automata
  • GNFAs are simply NFAs where the transition arrows may have regular expressions as labels rather than strictly symbols of the alphabet or \(\lambda\)
  • It reads blocks of symbols from the input, not just one symbol at a time
  • It will accept its input if the input causes the GNFA to end in an accepting state
  • A GNFA must always meet the following conditions:
    • The start state has transition arrows going to every other state but no arrows coming in from any other state
    • There is only one accept state that has arrows coming in from every other state but no arrows going to any other state. The accept state can not be the same as the start state
    • Except for the start and accept states, one arrow goes from every state to every other state and also from each state to itself
  • Converting from a DFA to a GNFA
    • Add a new start state with a \(\lambda\) arrow to the old start state
    • Add a new accept state with \(\lambda\) arrows coming from the old states
    • If there are any arrows with multiple labels or multiple arrows going between the same two states in the same direction, replace each arrow with one arrow whose label is the union of the previous ones
    • Add \(\varnothing\) arrows between states that had no arrows
  • GNFA Reductions
    • Because GNFAs must have one start and one accept states, we now that they must have at least two states (\(k \geq 2\) when \(k\) = number of states)
    • For \(k > 2\), we can construct a GNFA with \(k - 1\) states
    • We can continue removing states until there are only two
      • The arrow that will go between the start and accept states are equal to the regular expression that is accepted by the GNFA
    • Example:
    • The steps for this reduction are:
  • Formal Definition
    • A generalized nondeterministic finite automaton is a 5-tuple \((Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_{start}, q_{accept})\), where
      • \(Q\) is the finite set of states
      • \(\Sigma\) is the input alphabet
      • \(\delta: (Q - \{q_{accept}\}) \times (Q - \{q_{start}\}) \to R\) is the transition function where \(R\) is the collection of all regular expressions over the alphabet \(\Sigma\)
      • \(q_{start}\) is the start state
      • \(q_{accept}\) is the accept state

Pumping Lemma for Regular Languages

  • Certain languages can’t be recognized by any finite automaton, for example:
    \(B = \{0^n1^n | n \geq 0\}\)
    • When trying to make a DFA for this language, it is seen that you need to remember how many 0’s have been seen so far as it reads input- but the number of 0’s isn’t limited. You will have to keep track of an unlimited number of possibilities- but that can’t be done with a finite number of states
  • The Pumping Lemma is a way to prove that languages like these are not regular
    • The pumping lemma states that all regular languages have a special property, and that if we can show that a language doesn’t have this property, it is certain that this language is not regular.
    • The property is that all strings in the language can be “pumped” if they are at least as long as the pumping length
      • Each string contains a section that can be repeated as many number of times as desired and the resulting string will still be in the language
  • Pumping Lemma: The Theorem
    • If \(A\) is a regular language, then there is a number \(p\) (the pumping length) where if \(s\) is any string in \(A\) of length at least \(p\), then \(s\) may be divided into \(s = xyz\), such that:
      • For each \(i \geq 0\), \(xy^iz \in A\)
      • \(|y| > 0\)
      • \(|xy| \leq p\)
  • Pumping Lemma: The Proof
    • Let \(M = (Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_1, F)\) be a DFA recognizing \(A\) and \(P\) be the number of states in \(M\)
    • Let \(s = s_1s_2...s_n\) be a string in \(A\) of length \(n\) where \(n \geq p\)
    • Let \(r_1...r_{n+1}\) be the sequence of states that \(M\) enters while processing \(s\)
      • \(r_{i+1} = \delta(r_i, s_i)\) for \(1 \leq i \leq n\)
      • The sequence has length \(n+1\), which is at least \(p+1\)
    • Two of the first \(p+1\) elements in the sequence must be the same according to the pigeonhole principle
      • We call these elements \(r_j\) and \(r_l\)
      • \(r_l\) occurs among the first \(p+1\) places in the squence starting at \(r_1\) and therefore we can say that \(l \leq p + 1\)
    • Now let \(x = s_1...s_{j-1}, y = s_j...s_{l-1}, ~\text{and}~ z = s_l...s_n\)
      • As \(x\) takes \(M\) from \(r_1\) to \(r_j\), \(y\) takes \(M\) from \(r_j\) to \(r_j\), and \(z\) takes \(M\) from \(r_j\) to \(r_{n+1}\), which is an accept state
      • \(M\) must accept \(xy^iz\) for \(i \geq 0\)
      • We know that \(j \neq l\), so \(|y| > 0\)
      • We also know that \(l \leq p + 1\), so \(|xy| \leq p\)
    • Thus, all conditions for the pumping lemma are satisfied
  • How to use the pumping lemma
    • It is used to prove that a language is not regular, you should use proof by contradiction
      • First, assume that \(B\) is a regular language
      • State that because \(B\) is regular, it has a pumping length \(p\) and that all strings in \(B\) that at least length \(p\) can be pumped up or pumped down
      • Find a string \(s\) in \(B\) that has length \(p\) or greater that can not be pumped
      • Show that \(s\) can not be pumped by considering all ways of dividing \(s = xy^iz\)
        • For each division, show that there is a value of \(i\) such that \(xy^iz \notin B\)
    • The final conclusion should be that the existance of \(s\) contradicts the pumping lemma if \(B\) were regular, and therefore \(B\) is not regular

Context Free Languages

  • Context free languages are the collection of languages associated with context free grammars
  • They include all of the regular languages as well as many new languages

Context Free Grammars

  • A powerful method of describing languages
  • They can describe features that have a recursive structure
  • They have a component called a parser which can get the meaning of a program prior to compilation or execution
  • A context free grammar looks like:
  • Each line in the CFG represents a substitution rule, also known as a production
  • The symbol to the left of the arrow is called a variable and the strings to the right of the arrow are called terminals
    • Variables are often represented by capital letters
    • The terminals are similar to an input alphabet an often represented by lower case letters, numbers, or special symbols
    • One variable is designated as the start variable which usually occurs on the leftmost side of the topmost rule. In the above example, \(A\) is the start variable
  • You can use grammars to generate strings of a language by:
    • Write down the start variable
    • Find a variable that is written down and a rule that starts with that variable. Replace the written down variable with the right-hand side of that rule
    • Repeat step 2 until no variables remain
      • For example, the CFG above creates the string \(000\#111\)
    • The sequence of substitutions to obtain this string is called a derivation
      • \(A \rightarrow 0A1 \rightarrow 00A11 \rightarrow 000A111 \rightarrow 000B111 \rightarrow 000\#111\)
      • You can also represent this with a parse tree
    • All strings generated this way create the **language of the grammar* written as \(L(G)\)
      • The above example creates a language of \(\{0^n\#1^n|n \geq 0\}\)
  • Formal Definition:
    • A context free grammar is a 4-tuple \((V, \Sigma, R, S)\) where
      • \(V\) is a finite set called the variables
      • \(\Sigma\) is a finite set called the terminals
      • \(R\) is a finite set of rules
      • \(S \in V\) is the start variable
    • In the example grammar:
      • \(V = \{A, B\}\)
      • \(\Sigma = \{0, 1, \#\}\)
      • \(S = A\)
      • \(R\) is the collection of the three rules
  • Designing a context free grammar
    • Take the language \(L = \{0^n1^n | n \geq 0\} \cup \{1^n0^n | n \geq 0\}\), construct the grammar
      \(S_1 \to 0S_11 | \lambda\) for the first half of the union. Then construct the grammar \(S_2 \to 1S_20 | \lambda\) for the second half of the union
    • Add the rule \(S \to S_1 | S_2\) to give the final grammar:
    \[ S \to S_1 | S_2\\ S_1 \to 0S_11|\lambda\\ S_! \to 1S_20 | \lambda \]
  • Designing a context free grammar from a DFA
    • Make a variable \(R_i\) for each state \(q_i\) in the DFA
    • Add the rule \(R_i \to aR_j\) to the CFG if \(\delta(q_i, a) = q_j\) is the transition in the DFA
    • Add the rule \($R_i \to \lambda\) if \(q_i\) is an accept state of the DFA
    • Make \(R_o\) the start variable of the grammar, where \(q_o\) is the start state of the machine
    • Verify that the CFG generates the same language as the DFA recognizes
  • Ambiguity
    • A string that can be derived more than one way in the grammar is derived ambiguously
    • If a string is generated ambiguously, then the grammar is ambiguous
    • For example, the grammar \(\langle\text{EXPR}\rangle \to \langle\text{EXPR}\rangle + \langle\text{EXPR}\rangle | \langle\text{EXPR}\rangle \times \langle\text{EXPR}\rangle | \left(\langle\text{EXPR}\rangle\right)| a\)
      generates the string \(a+a \times a\) ambiguously. The following parse trees demonstrate two ways to get this string:
    • Ambiguity means two different parse trees, not two different derivations
      • A leftmost derivation is a derivation of a string where at every step, the leftmost remaining variable is the one replaced
    • Defintion 2.7: A string \(w\) is derived ambiguously in a context-free grammar \(G\) if it has two ore more different leftmost derivations. Grammar \(G\) is ambiguous if it generates some string ambiguously

Chomsky Normal Form

  • chomp chomp
  • Useful in giving algorithms for working with context free grammars
  • Formal definition:
    • A context free grammar is in chomsky normal form if every rule is of the form
      \(A \to BC\)
      \(A \to a\)
      where \(a\) is any terminal and \(A, B\), and \(C\) are any variables- except that \(B\) and \(C\) may not be the start variable. In addition, we permit the rule \(S \to \lambda\) where \(S\) is the start variable
  • Theorem: A context free language is generated by a context-free grammar in Chomsky Normal Form
  • Proof: First, add a new start variable \(S_o\) and the rule \(S_o \to S\)
    • Take care of all \(\lambda\) rules
      • We remove a \(\lambda\) rule \(A \to \lambda\) where \(A\) is not the start variable
      • For each \(A\) that appears on the right hand side of a rule, we add a new rule with that occurence deleted
        • For example, if \(R \to uAv\) is a rule we add the rule \(R \to uv\). It is done for each occurence of \(A\), so the rule \(R \to uAvAw\) causes us to add \(R \to uvAw\), \(R \to uAvw\), and \(R \to uvw\)
      • If we have the rule \(R \to A\), we had \(R \to \lambda\) unless we had previously removed the rule \(R \to \lambda\)
      • These steps are repeated until all \(\lambda\) rules are eliminated not including the starting variable
    • Handle all unit rules
      • Remove a unit rule \(A \to B\)
      • Whenever \(B \to u\) appears, add the rule \(A \to u\) unless it was a unit rule previously removed
      • Repeat these steps until all unit rules are eliminated
    • Convert the remaining rules into the proper form
      • Replace each rule \(A \to u_1u_2...u_k\) where \(k \geq 3\) and each \(u_i\) is a variable or terminal symbol, with the rules \(A \to u_1A_1, A_1 \to u_2A_2, A_2 \to u_3A_3, ..., A_{k-2} \to u_{k-1}u_j\)
        • The \(A's\) are nrew variables. We replace any terminal \(u\) in the preceding rule(s) with a new variable \(U_i \to u_i\)

Pushdown Automaton

  • Pushdown Automata is a class of machines recognizing context-free languages that can be useful by allowing us insight into the power of context free grammars
  • Similar to NFAs but have an extra component called a stack
    • The stack provides additional memory beyond the finite amount available in an NFA
    • Allows for recognition of nonregular languages
  • Equivalent in power to CFGs
    • Two options for proving that a language is context free: either give a CFG or PDA
  • PDA Schematic:
  • A PDA can write symbols on the stack and read them back later
    • Writing a symbol is “pushing it down” because it pushes down all of the other symbols on the stack. Any symbol on the top of the stack can be read and removed, the remaining symbols all move up
    • LIFO (last in first out) storage
  • A PDA can recognize the language \(\{0^n1^n | n \geq 0\}\) because the stack allows it to store the number of 0’s that have been seen. If you recall from earlier, we mentioned that finite automaton can not recognize this language due to limited memory
  • Formal Definition: A pushdown automaton is a 6-tuple \((Q, \Sigma, \Gamma, \delta, q_o, F)\) where \(Q, \Sigma, \Gamma, F\) are all finite sets, and:
    • \(Q\) is the set of states
    • \(\Sigma\) is the input alphabet
    • \(\Gamma\) is the stack alphabet
    • \(\delta: Q \times \Sigma_{\lambda} \times \Gamma_{\lambda} \to P(Q \times \Gamma_{\lambda})\) is the transition function,
    • \(q_o \in Q\) is the start state
    • \(F \subseteq Q\) is the set of accept states
  • The below PDA recognizes the language \(K = \{o^n1^n | n \geq 0\}\):

Equivalence with Context-Free Grammars

  • Theorem: A language is context free iff some pushdown automaton recognizes it
    • As usual with iff statements, you have to prove both sides of the statement
  • Theorem Part 1: If a language is context free, then some pushdown automaton recognizes it
    • Proof: Let \(Q\) and \(r\) be states of the PDA and let \(a\) be in \(\Sigma_{\lambda}\) and \(s\) be in \(\Gamma_{\lambda}\)
      • Say that we want the PDA to go from \(q\) to \(r\) when it reads \(a\) and pops \(s\)
        • We want to push the entire string \(u = u_1...u_l\) on the stack at the same time
        • We can implement this action by introducing new states \(q_1..q_{l-1}\) and setting the transition function as:
        \[ \delta(q, a, s) ~\text{to contain}~ (q_1, u_1)\\ \delta(q_1, \lambda, \lambda) = \{(q_2, u_{l-1})\}\\ \delta(q_2, \lambda, \lambda) = \{(q_3, u_{l-2})\}\\ \vdots\\ \delta(q_{l-1}, \lambda, \lambda) = \{(r, u_1)\} \]
        • where the following figure shows this implementation
        • From this implementation, we can come up with the state diagram that completes the proof
  • Theorem Part 2: If a pushdown automaton recognizes some language, then it is context free
    • Proof: Say that \(P = (Q, \Sigma, \Gamma, \delta, q_o, \{q_{accept}\})\) and construct \(G\). The variables of \(G\) are \(\{A_{pq} | p, q \in Q\}\). The start variable is \(A_{q_o, q_{accept}}\). Now we want to describe \(G's\) rules in three parts:
      • For each \(p, q, r, s \in Q, u \in \Gamma\), and \(a, b \in \Sigma_{\lambda}\) if \(\delta(p, a, \lambda)\) contains \((r, u)\) and \(\delta(s, b, u)\) contains \((q, e)\), put the rule \(A_{pq} \to aA_{rs}b\) in \(G\)
      • For each \(p, q, r \in Q\), put the rule \(A_{pq} \to A_{pr}A_{rq}\) in \(G\)
      • For each \(p \in Q\), put the rule \(A_{pp} \to \lambda\) in \(G\)
      • The following images may help with the understanding

Pumping Lemma for Context Free Languages

  • The pumping lemma states that every context free language has a special value called the pumping length such that all longer strings in the language can be pumped
    • Being pumped is a little different in this sense; it means that the string can be divided into five parts (rather than three) so that the second and fourth parts may be repeated together any number of times such that the resulting string is still in the language
  • Theorem: Pumping Lemma
    • If \(A\) is a context free language, then there is a number \(p\) (the pumping length) where, if any string \(s\) is in \(A\) with length at least \(p\), then \(s\) may be divided into five pieces: \(s=uv^ixy^iz\) such that \(s\) satisfies the following conditions:
      • for each \(i \geq 0, uv^ixy^iz \in A\)
      • \(|vy| > 0\)
      • \(|vxy| \leq p\)
  • Proof: Pumping Lemma
    • Let \(G\) be a CFG for CFL \(A\)
    • Let \(b\) be the maximum number of symbols in the right-hand side of a rule (assume at least 2)
      • In any parse tree using this grammar, we know that:
        • The height of the parse tree is at most \(h\) where \(h\) is the number of steps between the start variable and the leaf nodes
        • The length of the string generated is at most \(b^h\)
    • Say that \(|V|\) is the number of variables in \(G\)
      • We set \(p\) to be at least \(b^{|V| + 1}\)
      • If \(s \in A\) and \(|s| \geq p\), the parse tree must be at least \(|V| + 1\) high
        • This is because \(b^{|V| + 1} \geq b^{|V|} + 1\)
    • To see how to pump any string \(s\) that meets the above requirements, let \(\tau\) be one of its parse trees
      • If \(s\) has several parse trees, choose \(\tau\) to be a parse three with the smallest number of nodes
      • We know that \(\tau\) must be at least \(|V| + 1\) high
        • This means the longest path from the root to a leaf is at least \(|V| + 1\)
      • Because \(G\) only has \(|V|\) variables, we know that there will be some variable \(R\) that will appear more than once on that path
    • Divide \(s\) into \(uvxyz\) as stated above
      • Each recurrence of \(R\) has a larger subtree that generates \(xvy\) and the lower occurrence generates just \(x\) with a smaller subtree
        • Both of these subtrees are generated by the same variable so we can make substitutions and still have a valid parse tree
          • Replacing the smaller tree by the larger tree gives parse trees for the string \(uv^ixy^iz\) at each \(i > 1\)
          • Replacing the larger tree by the smaller tree gives parse trees for the string \(uxz\)
        • This establishes the proof for the first condition of the lemma
    • For the second condition, we need to ensure that \(v\) and \(y\) are not both \(\lambda\)
      • If they were to both be \(\lambda\), the parse tree obtained by substituting the smaller tree for the larger tree would have fewer nodes than \(\tau\) does and it would still generate \(s\)
        • This isn’t possible because we had already chosen \(\tau\) to be a parse tree for \(s\) with the smallest possible number of nodes; that is why we chose \(\tau\) to be that way
    • For the third condition, we need to make sure that \(vxy\) isn’t any larger than \(p\)
      • In the parse tree for \(s\), the upper occurrence of \(R\) generates \(vxy\)
      • We also chose \(R\) so that both occurrences fall within the bottom of \(|V| + 1\) variables on the path and we chose the longest path in the parse tree
        • This means that the subtree where \(R\) generates \(vxy\) is at most \(|V| + 1\) high
        • A tree of this height can generate a string of length, at most, \(b^{|V| + 1 } = p\)

Turing Machines

  • Turing machines are similar to a finite automaton but have unlimited and unrestricted memory
  • Much more accurate model of a general purpose computer
  • Can do everything that a real computer can do
  • Uses an infinite tape as its unlimited memory; has a tape head that can read and write symbols and move around the tape
    • Initially the tape contains only the input string and is blank everywhere else
    • If the machine eneds to store information, it may write it on the tape
    • To read information it has written, the machine can move its head back over the tape
    • Continues computing until it decides to produce an output
      • The output is either accept or reject and is obtained by entering designated accepting or rejecting states
      • If it never reaches an accepting or rejecting state, it will continue forever and never halt
    • The schematic of a turing machine is:

      • The \(\sqcup\) are blank spaces that the turing machine can write on
  • Summary of differences between finite automata and turing machines:
    • Turing machines can both read and write on a tape
    • The read-write head can move both to the left and right
    • The tape is infinite
    • The special states for accepting and rejecting take place immediately
  • Example: \(L = \{w\#w | w \in \{0, 1\}^*\}\)
    • We want to make a turing machine, call it \(M\), that accepts input if it is a member of \(L\), otherwise reject it
    • \(M\) = “On input string \(w\):
      • Zig-zag across the tape to the corresponding positions on either side of the \(\#\) symbol and check whether these positions contain the same symbol. If they do not, or if no \(\#\) is found, reject. Cross off symbols as they are checked to keep track of which symbols correspond
      • When all symbols to the left of the \(\#\) have been crossed off, check for any remaining symbols on the right of the \(\#\). If any symbols remain, reject. Otherwise, accept"
    • The following picture demonstrates the process for \(M's\) tape after reading input \(011000\#011000\)

  • Formal Definition:
    • A turing machine is a 7-tuple, \((Q, \Sigma, \Gamma, \delta, q_o, q_{accept}, q_{reject})\), where \(Q, \Sigma, \Gamma\) are all finite sets and:
      • \(Q\) is the set of states
      • \(\Sigma\) is the input alphabet that does not contain the blank symbol \(\sqcup\)
      • \(\Gamma\) is the tape alphabet, where \(\sqcup \in \Gamma\) and \(\Sigma \subseteq \Gamma\)
      • \(\delta: Q \times \Gamma \to Q \times \Gamma \times \{L, R\}\) is the transition function
      • \(q_o \in Q\) is the start state
      • \(q_{accept} \in Q\) is the accept state
      • \(q_{reject} \in Q\) is the reject state, where \(q_{reject} \neq q_{accept}\)
  • The configuration of a turing machine is a setting of the computation, changes in the current state, and the current tape contents
  • Configurations are represented as \(uqv\) for a state \(q\) and two strings \(u\) and \(v\) over the tape alphabet \(\Gamma\)
    • The current state is \(q\), the current tape contents is \(uv\), and the current head location is the first symbol of \(v\)
      • The tape contains blank symbols following the last symbol of \(v\)
    • For example: \(1011q_701111\) represents the configuration when the tape is \(101101111\)
      • The current state is \(q_7\) and the head is currently on the second \(0\). The below figure represents this configuration

Recognizable

  • We call a language turing-recognizable if some turing machine recognizes it
  • Three outcomes are possible from a turing machine: accept, reject, or loop
    • By loop, it is meant that the machine does not halt (it never reaches an accept or reject state)
  • A machine can fail to accept an input by entering the \(q_{reject}\) state or by looping
    • It can be difficult to determine if a machine is looping or if it is just taking a long time, so it is preferable to have a machine halt on all inputs
      • This means they would never loop
    • Machines that halt one very input are called deciders because they make a decision for every input; these machines are also said to decide that language

Decidable

  • We call a language turing-decidable (or simply decidable) if some turing machine decides it
  • Any language that is decidable is also recognizable, but not vice versa
  • Example:
    • Describe a turing machine \(M\) that decides \(L = \{O^{2^n} | n \geq 0\}\), aka the language consiting of all strings of \(0's\) whose length is a power of \(2\)
      • \(M\) = “On input string \(w\):
        • Sweep left to right across the tape, crossing off every other 0
        • If in stage 1 and the tape contained a single \(0\), accept
        • If in stage 1 and the tape contained more than a single \(0\) and the number of \(0's\) was odd, reject
        • Return the head to the left-hand end of the tape
        • Go to stage 1"
      • Each iteration of stage 1 cuts the number of \(0's\) in half
      • As the machine sweeps across the tape in stage 1, it keeps track of the number of \(0's\) seen is even or odd
        • If the number is both odd and greater than \(1\), it rejects
        • If the number is \(1\), it accepts
      • Formal definition of \(M = (Q, \Sigma, \Gamma, \delta, q_1, q_{accept}, q_{reject})\):
        • \(Q = \{q_1, q_2, q_3, q_4, q_5, q_{accept}, q_{reject}\}\)
        • \(\Sigma = \{0\}\)
        • \(\Gamma = \{0, x, \sqcup\}\)
        • \(\delta\) is described with the state diagram below
        • \(q_1\) is the start state, \(q_{accept}\) is the accept state, \(q_{reject}\) is the reject state

      • The following image is a series of configurations of \(M\) when ran on input \(0000\)

Multitape Turing Machines

  • A multitape turing machine is like an ordinary turing machine with more than one tape
    • Each tape has its own head for reading and writing
    • Initially the input is on tape 1 and the others are blank; the transition function is changed to allow for reading, writing, and moving the heads on some or all of the tapes. The formal definition of the transition function is:

    \[ \delta: Q \times \Gamma^k \to Q \Gamma^k \times \{L, R, S\}^k \]

    • k is the number of tapes. The expression below means that if the machine is in state \(q_i\) and the heads \(1\) through \(k\) are reading symbols \(a_1\) through \(a_k\), the machine goes to state \(q_j\), writes symbols \(b_1\) through \(b_k\), and directs each head to move left, right, or stay put as specified:

    \[ \delta(q_i, a_1, ..., a_k) = (q_j, b_1, ..., b_k, L, R, ..., L) \]

  • Even though it may seem that multitape machines are more powerful than single tap machines, they have the same amount of power
  • Theorem: Every multitape turing machine has an equivalent single-tape turing machine
  • Proof: Show how to convert a multitape turing machine \(M\) to an equivalent single-tape turing machine \(S\). We need to show how to simulate \(M\) with \(S\)
    • Say that \(M\) has \(k\) tapes- then \(S\) simulates the effect of \(k\) tapes by storing their information on its single tape
      • It uses the new symbol \(\#\) as a delimiter to separate the contents of the different tapes
    • S must also keep track of the head locations for the multiple tapes
      • This is achieved by writing a tape symbol with a dot above it to mark the place where the head would be
    • The following figure demonstrates how this is done:

  • Example:
    • \(S\) = “On input \(w = w_1...w_n\)
      • First \(S\) puts its tape into the format that represents all \(k\) tapes of \(M\). The formatted tape contains:
      \[ \#\dot{w_1}w_2 \dotsm w_n\#\dot{\sqcup}\#\dot{\sqcup}\# \dotsm \# \]
      • To simulate a move:
        • \(S\) scans its tape from the first \(\#\) which marks the left-hand end
        • It continues to scan until the \((k+1)^{st}\) \(\#\) which marks the right-hand end
          • This determines the symbols under the heads
        • \(S\) makes a second pass to update the tapes according to the way that \(M\) dictates
      • If \(S\) moves one of the heads right onto a \(\#\), it means that \(M\) has moved the corresponding head onto the blank portion of the tape, so \(S\) writes a blank symbol on this tape cell and shifts the contents one unit to the right, then continues as before"

Nondeterministic Turing Machines

  • At any point in a computation, the machine may proceed according to several possibilities (similar to nondeterministic finite automata)
  • The transition function is: \(\delta: Q \times \Gamma \to P(Q \times \Gamma \times \{L, R\})\)
  • As a refresh on what it means to be nondeterministic:
    • A nondeterministic machine has several choices for the next state at any given point
    • The machine will split into multiple copies of itself and follow all possibilities at the same time, in parallel
    • If there is nowhere for the input to go, that branch of the machine dies
    • If any branch of the machine is accepted, the machine accepts the input

Enumerators

  • An enumerator if a turing machine with an attached printer which can be used as an output device to print strings
  • Any time the turing machine wants to add a string to the list, it sends the string to the printer. The schematic is:

  • An enumerator starts with a blank input
    • If it doesn’t halt, it may print an infinite list of strings
    • The language enumerated is a collection of all of the strings that it eventually outputs
    • It may generate the strings of the language in any order and it may have repititions
  • Theorem: A language is turing recognizable iff some enumerator enumerates it
  • Proof:
    • First, show that we have an enumerator \(E\) that enumerates a language \(A\). There is a turing machine \(M\) recognizes \(A\). \(M\) works in the following way:
      • \(M\) = “On input \(w\):
        • Run \(E\). Every time that \(E\) outputs a string, compare it to \(w\)
        • If \(w\) ever appears in the output of \(E\), accept"
      • \(M\) accepts those strings that appear on \(E's\) list
    • Look at the other direction of the iff. If a turing machine \(M\) recognizes a language \(A\), we can construct the enumerator \(E\) for \(A\). Say that \(s_1, s_2, s_3, ...\) is a list of all of the possible strings in \(\Sigma^*\)
      • \(E\) = “Ignore the input
        • Repeat the following process for \(i \in \mathbb{N}\):
          • Run \(M\) for \(i\) steps on each input $s_1, s_2, s_3, …, s_i
          • If any computations accept, print out the corresponding \(s_j\)"
      • If \(M\) accepts a particular string \(s\), eventually it will appear on the list that \(E\) outputs; it will actually appear infinitely many times because \(M\) runs from the beginning on each string for each repitition of step 1. It gives the effect of \(M\) running in parallel on all possible input strings

Equivalence with Other Models

  • Each variance of the turing machine has equal power
  • All models that feature unlimited memory end up being equivalent in power as long as they satisfy reasonable requirements
    • An analogy: Is there an algorithm that can be programmed in one language but not another?
      • No, all reasonable programming languages have the power to create the same algorithms (they’re just not always created the exact same way)
      • You could say that languages describe exactly the same class of algorithms
    • This analogy holds for computational models as well
      • Any two computational models that satisfy certain reasonable requirements can simulate one another and therefore are equivalent in power
  • Important corollary: Even though we can imagine different types of computational models, the class of algorithms that they describe remains the same

Definition of an Algorithm

  • An algorithm is a collection of simple instructions where the purpose is to carry out some task
    • Sometimes they are called procedures or recipes in everyday life
    • They are also important in mathematics
  • Hilbert’s Problem
    • A set of 23 mathematical problems that were posed as a challenge for the coming century in 1900.
    • The \(10^{th}\) problem on the list was about algorithms
      • Devise an algorithm that tests whether a polynomial has an integer root
      • He assumed that this was possible- all that had to be done was someone being able to construct the method
        • Plot twist: he was wrong. There isn’t an algorithm that can do this
        • Mathematitions at that time wouldn’t have been able to prove that it is impossible because they didn’t even have the definition of an algorithm
      • Fast forward to 1936- the Church Turing thesis. They defined an algorithm
        • Church did it with \(\lambda\)-calculus and Turing did it with his machines and the definitions were shown to be equivalent
      • Fast forward again to 1970- Yuri Matijasevic built on the work of Martin Davis, Hilary Putnam, and Julia Robinson to show that there wasn’t an algorithm to determine whether a polynomial has integral roots
    • Rephrase Hilbert’s tenth problem in our own terminology
    \[ D = \{p~ | ~p \text{ is a polynomial with an integral root}\} \]
    • The problem essentially asks: is \(D\) decidable? No, it’s not. However, we can show that it is recognizable
      • Also, if \(D\) was univariate it would be decidable

Decidability

  • Decidability and Regular Languages
    • With regular languages, we give algorithms for testing if a finite automaton accepts a string, if a language of a finite automaton is empty, and if two finite automata are equivalent
    • The acceptance problem
      • The acceptance problem for DFAs tests whether or not a particular DFA accepts a given string
      • This problem can be expressed as a language, \(A_{DFA}\)
        • The language has all of the encodings of all DFAs together with strings that the DFAs accept \[ A_{DFA} = \{\langle B, w \rangle | B \text{ is a DFA that accepts input string } w\} \]
      • Theorem: \(A_{DFA}\) is a decidable language
        • Proof idea: We need to present a turing machine \(M\) that decides \(A_{DFA}\):
          • \(M\) = “On input \(\langle B, w \rangle\), where \(B\) is a DFA and \(w\) is a string:
            • Simulate \(B\) on input \(w\)
            • If the simulation ends in an accept state, accept. If it ends in a non-accepting state, reject"
      • Theorem: \(A_{NFA}\) is a decidable language
        • Proof idea: We need to present a turing machine \(N\) that decides \(A_{NFA}\)
          • \(N\) = “On input \(\langle B, w \rangle\), where \(B\) is an NFA and \(w\) is a string:
            • Convert NFA \(B\) to an equivalent DFA \(C\)
            • Run the turing machine \(M\) from the above theorem on input \(\langle C, w \rangle\)
            • If \(M\) accepts, accept. Otherwise, reject"
      • Theorem: \(A_{REX}\) is a decidable language
        • Proof idea: We need to present a turing machine \(P\) that decides \(A_{REX}\)
          • \(P\) = “On input \(\langle R, w \rangle\) where \(R\) is a regular expression and \(w\) is a string:
            • Convert \(R\) into an equivalent NFA \(A\)
            • Run the turing machine \(N\) from the above theorem on input \(\langle A, w \rangle\)
            • If \(N\) accepts, accept. If \(N\) rejects, reject"
    • Emptiness Testing: \(E_{DFA} = \{\langle A \rangle | A \text{ is a DFA and } L(A) = \varnothing\}\)
      • Theorem: \(E_{DFA}\) is a decidable language
        • Proof Idea: You need to design some turing machine \(T\) that does shit, idk
          • \(T\) = “On input \(\langle A \rangle\) where \(A\) is a DFA:
            • Mark the start state of \(A\)
            • Repeat until no new states get marked
              • Mark any state that has a transition coming into it from any state that is already marked
            • If no accept state is marked, accept. Otherwise, reject"
      • Let \(EQ_{DFA} = \{\langle A, B \rangle | A \text{ and } B \text{ are DFAs and } L(A) = L(B)\}\)
      • Theorem: \(EQ_{DFA}\) is a decidable language
        • Proof Idea: Create a DFA \(C\) from \(A\) and \(B\) where \(C\) accepts strings that are accepted by either \(A\) or \(B\) but not both
          • \(F\) = “On input \(\langle A, B\rangle\) where \(A\) and \(B\) are DFAs:
            • Construct a DFA \(C\) as described
            • Run turing machine \(T\) from the above proof on input \(\langle C\rangle\)
            • If \(T\) accepts, acccept. If \(T\) rejects, reject"

  • Decidability and Context Free Languages
    • Acceptance Problem : \(A_{CFG} = \{\langle G, w \rangle | G \text{ is a CFG that generates string } w\}\)
      • Theorem: \(A_{CFG}\) is a decidable language
        • Proof idea: Convert \(G\) into Chomsky Normal Form by creating a turing machine \(S\) for \(A_{CFG}\) as follows:
          • \(S\) = “On input \(\langle G, w \rangle\) where \(G\) is a CFG and \(w\) is a string:
            • Convert \(G\) to an equivalent grammar in Chomsky normal form"
            • List all derivations with \(2n - 1\) steps where \(n\) is the length of \(w\)
              • Unless \(n = 0\), then list all derivations with one step
            • If any of these derivations generate \(w\), accept. Otherwise, reject
    • Emptiness Testing: \(E_{CFG} = \{\langle G \rangle | G \text{ is a CFG and } L(G) = \varnothing\}\)
      • Theorem: \(E_{CFG}\) is a decidable language
        • Proof Idea: Create turing machine \(R\) that marks all of the terminal symbols in the grammar, scans for all of the rules in the grammar, and marks any variables in rules of which there is a variable that can be replaced by some string of symbols
          • \(R\) = “On input \(\langle G\rangle\) where \(G\) is a CFG:
            • Mark all terminal symbols in \(G\)
            • Repeat until no new variables get marked:
              • Mark any variable \(A\) where \(G\) has a rul \(A \to U_1U_2 \dotsm U_K\) and each symbol \(U_1, ..., U_k\) has already been marked
            • If the start variable is not marked, accept. Otherwise, reject"
      • Let \(EQ_{CFG} = \{\langle G, H \rangle | G \text{ and } H \text{ are CFGs and } L(G) = L(H)\}\)
      • Theorem: Every context-free language is decidable
        • Proof Idea: Use the turing machine \(S\) from a couple theorems ago. Let \(G\) be a CFG for \(A\) and design a turing machine \(M_G\) that decides \(A\)
          • \(M_G\) = “On input \(w\):
            • Run \(S\) on input \(\langle G, w\rangle\)
            • If \(S\) accepts, accept. If it rejects, reject"

Undecidability

  • Set Theory Notations and Definitions:
    • Given two sets \(A\) and \(B\) and a function \(f\) from \(A\) to \(B\)
      • We say that \(f\) is one to one (or injective) if it never maps two different elements to the same place
        • i.e. \(f(a) \neq f(b)\) when \(a \neq b\)
        • Two unique \(x\) values will never have the same \(y\) values
      • We say that \(f\) is onto (or surjective) if it hits every element of \(B\)
        • i.e. for every \(b \in B\) there is an \(a \in A\) such that \(f(a) = b\)
      • We say that \(f\) is bijective if it is both one to one and onto
    • We say that a set \(A\) is countable if it is either finite or has the same cardinality as \(\mathbb{N}\)
    • Theorem: \(\mathbb{R}\) is the set of real numbers, show that \(\mathbb{R}\) is uncountable
      • Proof: We need to show that there is no existing correspondence between \(\mathbb{N}\) and \(\mathbb{R}\) which will be a proof by contradiction; show that \(f\) fails to work as it should
        • We need to create an \(x\) so that each digit makes \(x\) different from one of the real numbers that is paired with an element of \(\mathbb{N}\)
        • Example: Suppose that the correspondence \(f\) exists
          • Let \(f(1) = 3.14159..., f(2) = 55.55555...., f(3) = ....,\) and so on
          • The following table shows the hypothetical correspondence \(f\) between \(\mathbb{N}\) and \(\mathbb{R}\)
          • The desired \(x\) is constructed with decimal representation
            • It is a number between \(0\) and \(1\) so all of its significant digits are fractional digits following the decimal
            • We want to ensure that \(x \neq f(n)\) for any \(n\)
              • We do this by making sure that the \(n^{th}\) digit of \(x\) is anything but the first digit of \(f(n)\)
                • i.e. for \(f(1)\), we would want \(x\) to be, say, \(3.44159...\), for \(f(2)\) we would want \(x\) to be, say, \(55.54555...\)
                • We never want an \(x\) value to be \(0\) or \(9\) so we can avoid rounding issues
          • Doing this down the diagonal of the table for \(f\) we can get all of the digits of \(x\) in such a way that we know \(x \neq f(n)\)
